[2
Date: Tue, 25 May 1999 21:35:36 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: News media, 25 May 1999

[Two cheese recalls in the same day. Interesting in the wake of the USDA
guidelines for meat released today. -MPP
*****
A small Missouri dairy is recalling 135 pounds of specialty cheese that may
be contaminated with dangerous listeria.
Morningland Dairy Farms Inc., based in Mountain View, Mo., said the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration has temporarily closed its cheese-making
operations.
In Raleigh, N.C., state officials reported a recall of a quantity of
imported cheese after tests found evidence of the same bacteria in it.
Routine testing at a grocery store revealed the _Listeria monocytogenes_
pathogen in Pinna Ricotta Salata Cheese, made with 100% sheep's milk.
The Missouri recall involved Morningland Dairy Chives Colby Cheese, which
authorities said should be returned for refunds to retailers who sold it.
The cheese is made from raw milk, and contamination showed up in tests by
federal health officials.
Calls to the company went unanswered Tuesday. A recorded message said: "The
FDA has temporarily shut down the cheese-making facility. We will not be
shipping for a couple weeks for sure. Call us back after that to find out
how we are doing. Sorry."
Listeria can cause serious, potentially fatal, infections in young
children, the elderly and people with weak immune systems. It also can
cause miscarriages. Healthy people, however, usually suffer short-term
symptoms, including diarrhea, nausea, abdominal pain and fever.
The recalled Colby cheese, sold in vacuum-packed plastic bags, carries the
code A259 on the label. It was sold by mail and in retail stores in
Missouri, Colorado, Utah, Illinois, Arizona, Tennessee, New York,
California, Georgia, Maryland, Pennsylvania and South Carolina.
No illnesses have been reported from the cheese recalled in North Carolina,
which was imported from Italy distributed by Anco Foods of Fairfield, N.J.
The Food and Drug Protection Division of the North Carolina Department of
Agriculture and Consumer Services advised consumers not to use the product
in packaging bearing the code "Sell by Sep 18, 99."
The cheese also may have been distributed in South Carolina, Georgia,
Florida, Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana and Tennessee.
